TikTok hides unwanted videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18.
Imagine China / Reuters
The Chinese social network TikTok is censoring videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibet’s independence or the banned religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian reports.
In the documents found in the publication, it is said that the owner of TikTok (company ByteDance) using the app promotes the goals of China’s foreign policy abroad.
Most of the violations related to China’s policy fall under the “burning of hatred.”
In each case, TikTok places inappropriate publications in a context appropriate to the general rules, so that the actions of the social network do not look censorship.
For example, the ban on criticism of the socialist system of China falls under the general ban of “criticism or attack on the politics and social rules of any country, such as constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc.”
The ban on mentioning incidents in Tianjinmen Square or the genocide in Cambodia falls under “the story of China or other countries.”
The document also lists the President of the President of the Republic of Korea, Azoy Nayyi, and the President of the Republic of Korea, Nayyi Nayi, and the President of the Republic of Korea, Nayi Nayi, and the President of the Republic of Korea, Nayyi Nayi, and the Presidents of India, Mahatma Gandhi, Presidents of the United States, Donald Trump, and Baron.
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, said in the document.
Posts from the first category are removed by the administrators of the social network and may result in the blocking of the user.
Not too strict violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited by TikTok algorithms.
Representatives of ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer apply: "We are now using a localized approach to moderation, as well as attracting independent local specialists."
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publication, says co-founder of the “Producer Center” Rustem Bogdanov.
“Producer Center” is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Producer Center" agrees with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be placed without agreement, Bogdanov reports.
Asked whether TikTok can say anything about politics or Putin, Bogdanov said yes and said he had seen such publications.
Bogdanov agrees with the founder of the agency Our Didgital Roman Zaripov: "The basic rules for users TikTok lists in the user agreement: it is not possible to express shocking content, discriminatory statements and so on."
But under these rules you can put any content that does not like moderators, notes Zaripov.
Zaripova Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
By user agreement, only persons over the age of 13 can use TikTok.
Social network administrators check their age using artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, Bogdanov says.
If the neuronet decides that the user is younger, his account can be removed, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of coworking WeWork.
