“It’s heavy oil.
It can be discarded from one of the ships after cleaning the tanks.
Many continue to do so.
And most likely it got into the ocean current," said the coordinator of the trade union of workers of the oil industry of the states of Pernambuco and Paraiba, Roger Almeida, to the Brazilian news portal G1.
He also added that, despite the ban on this practice, many ships continue to dispose of waste in the open sea.
On the beaches of four of the eight affected states in the north-east of the country, environmentalists discovered nine sea turtles, completely covered with oil film.
Only two of them were rescued.
In the coming days, the Brazilian Institute of the Environment, together with the company Petrobras, will begin cleaning the contaminated beaches.
Meanwhile, the Institute’s specialists recommend tourists and locals to bypass the oil spills and warn about all the spots of pollution.
